The Telegraph - Calcutta : Bengal
 Friday, April 02, 2004 				 Handle with care plea for Maoist
 OUR BUREAU																								Siliguri, April 1: The Maoists have urged Darjeeling police to treat their arrested chief, Mohan Baidya, with respect since he had not committed any crime on the Indian soil.																								Expressing concern over the treatment that would be meted out to Baidya, who comes third in the hierarchy of the Nepal Communist Party (Maoist), chief Maoist negotiator Krishna Bahadur Mahara said: We are dismayed by Mohan Baidyas arrest by the West Bengal police. However, we urge the Indian authorities to treat him with respect as he is senior political leader of a neighbouring country and has committed no crime on Indian soil... 																								Baidya is not a fighter. He is a senior ideologue of the party and he should be treated with respect, Mahara said from a central Nepal hideout. Asked about the shelters set up by the rebels in Darjeeling, Dooars and Sikkim, Mahara said: That is a very technical question...
